INTRODUCTION

Worldwide forests provide key ecological, economical and socio-cultural services provided by forest ecosystems, and they support astonishing biodiversity. Recent studies have however pointed out that forest ecosystems face nowadays drastic changes, both from climatic and anthropogenic origins, and that these changes may impact ecosystem services at different time and spatial scales (for instance see Elkin et al. 2013). Understanding how forest will adapt to these changes and how forest management can help to mitigate these impacts is crucial and requires long-term monitoring of forest dynamics. The data set we present consists in a network of 64 forest permanent plots in the French northern Alps (Fig. 1). In this region, forests cover 41% of the area and climate exhibits high regional variations both along a continentality and an elevation gradient, with mediterranean influences in the south. In the network, tree species composition change with elevation, from European beech (Fagus sylvatica) dominated stands at the lower montane (800 m a.s.l) belt to Norway spruce (Picea abies) dominated stands at the subalpine belt (1 700 m a.s.l), through mixed stands of European beech, Silver fir (Abies alba) and Norway spruce at intermediate elevations. Archives analysis, using maps from the beginning of the 19th century and aerial photographs of the middle of the 20th century, have attested that French Alps forests are dominated by ancient forests that have been continuously forested for more than 200 years (Janssen et al. 2016). Dominant management system in these forests is uneven-aged management and consists in single-tree or small-group selection cutting. Moreover, harvesting rate has been very low for the last 150 years, because the protection function of the forest was the major objective and because of the decrease in wood price. In comparison with other European forests, forests in this area are thus generally richer in large and old trees and in deadwood and stand structure is rather heterogeneous (Paillet et al. 2015). Consequently, they are considered as biodiversity hotspots (EEA 2010, Barbati et al. 2014) of high protection, conservation, and economical values. In contrast, recent forests that have established in former agricultural lands or that originate from man-made rehabilitation of degraded lands at the end of the 19th century now consist in stands 120–180 years old that are still dominated by the first cohort of trees and show a quite regular structure and a high basal area that may locally reach more than 60 m2.ha-1. These two contrasted structural types dominates the network.

Plots were established from 1994 to 2004 and measured 2 to 5 times during the 1994-2015 period. Plots were initially established to sample a wide range of forest structure and successional stages to evaluate the forest dynamics across succession. They were then used to calibrate a forest dynamic model Samsara2 (Courbaud et al. 2015) and to test various silviculture practices. They are now also used to evaluate various ecosystem services (habitat quality, protection against natural hazard efficiency,…). The network now represents an invaluable tool to evaluate the response of mountain forest ecosystems to the combined effect of climate and management changes.

2. Abstract:

We present repeated tree measurement data from 63 permanent plots in mountain forests in France. Plot elevation ranges from 800 (lower limit of the montane belt) to 1942 m a.s.l (subalpine belt). Forest types mainly consists of pure or mixed stands dominated by European beech (Fagus sylvatica), Silver fir (Abies alba) and Norway spruce (Picea abies), in association with various broadleaved species at low elevation and with Arolla pine (Pinus cembra) at high elevation. The plot network includes 23 plots that have not been managed for the last 40 years (at least) and 23 plots managed according to an uneven-aged system in single-tree or small-group selection cutting. Plot sizes range from to 0.25 ha to 1.88 ha. Plots were installed from 1994 to 2004 and measured 2 to 5 times during the 1994-2015 period. During the first census (installation), living trees more than 7.5 cm in dbh were identified, their diameter at breast height (dbh) was measured and their social status (strata) noted. Trees were spatially located, either with x, y and z coordinates (41 plots) or within subplots 0.25 ha square (23 plots). In addition, in a subset of plots, tree heights and tree crown dimensions were measured on a subset of trees and dead standing trees and stumps were included in the census. During the following census, living tree diameters were measured (including recruited trees), tree status (living, damaged, dead, stump) were recorded, and for a subset of tree heights were remeasured. At the establishment of the plots, plot densities ranges from 180.8 to 1328 stems.ha-1 and plot basal areas ranges from 13.63 to 81.29 m2.ha-1 .

D. Key words

France; permanent plot; mountain forest; tree recruitment; tree growth; tree mortality; tree diameter; tree height; tree canopy radius; tree canopy height; forest management; tree spatial coordinates.

METADATA CLASS II. RESEARCH ORIGIN DESCRIPTORS

A. “OVERALL” PROJECT DESCRIPTION

1. Identity: Long-term stem inventory data from mountain forest plots in France.

2. Originators:

The study was first initiated by IRSTEA in collaboration with the French National Forest Office (public institute in charge of the management of public forests in France).

3. Period of study: From 1994 to 2015.

4. Objectives: The objectives are to monitor and analyse changes in forest structure and dynamics for a broad range of stand types in response to changes in management practices and climate conditions in the mountain forests of the French northern Alps.

Initial this was motivated by a change in management regime in the French Alps. Forest management has become very cautious in the French Alps during the 20th century: first, in order to maintain a constant canopy cover that warranty protection against natural hazards (Cordonnier et al. 2008), second because logging operations have become less and less profitable in remote or steep sloped areas. Consequently, mature forest stands dominated by large and very large ageing trees have developed and nowadays cover large areas.

Forest managers have gradually worried on the stability of these stands from the 80’s, fearing that a brutal senescent phase – both in space and time – may occasion large gaps and then be detrimental to the protective function of the forest (Leclerc and Millot 1998). Consequently, IRSTEA started in the 90’s a research program that aimed at assessing forest stability (resistance and resilience) and developing silvicultural guidelines that maintain or enhance stability.

With ongoing climate change, the network is also providing important information to monitor changes in mountain forests.

This dataset has also been used for a wide variety of objectives such as: MARC CELA ME SEMBLE TRES LONG EST PAS SUPER INTERESSANT POUR LE READER, NON?

  • To calibrate and validate an individual-based and spatially explicit forest dynamics simulation model, called Samsara2, and currently calibrated for Silver fir and Norway spruce (Vieilledent et al. 2010a, 2010b, Courbaud et al. 2015).

  • To traine forest manager of ONF, with simulation of harvesting with Samsara2.

  • To assess the protection efficiency of the forest against rockfall along a maturity gradient: we constituted homogeneous groups of plots regarding maturity structural attributes and used a rockfall simulation model that simulates impacts against trees and takes into account the species, the diameter and the location (x,y) of the trees (Fuhr et al. 2015).

  • To calibrate and validate predictive models of forest stand attributes (height distributions, diameter distributions, basal area, volume, individuals trees location) developed using airborne LiDAR data (Eysn et al. 2015).

  • To build habitat quality indicators using the dendrometric structure of the plots, combined with data on deadwood (Redon et al. 2014).

  • To test heterogeneity and abundance indices in heterogeneous mountain forest stands in order to link these indices to silvicultural practices and stand history (Cordonnier et al. 2012).

6. Sources of funding:

Plot installation and early monitoring was mainly supported by IRSTEA and ONF internal fundings. Complementary funds from the French Ministry of Environment, the French Ministry of Agriculture and the Vanoise National Park have recently helped for recent census and database developmenmt.

B. SPECIFIC SUBPROJECT DESCRIPTION

II.B.1. Census of stems ≥7.5 cm DBH

1. Sites description:

Plots are located in the northern French Alps. Plot location (see Table. 1) is either based on measurement with a differential GPS or an estimation of the position on a 1/25000 map. Ecological conditions are very heterogeneous (Table. 1). Climate is under oceanic (high precipitations all year long), continental (low precipitations, high seasonality of the temperature) and mediterranean (high temperatures and low precipitations) influences and can be divided into 5 climatic sectors: external northern sector with an oceanic climate, external southern sector with an oceanic-mediterranean climate, intermediate northern sector with an oceanic-continental climate, internal sector with a continental climate and intermediate southern sector mixing the influences of the three climates. Geology is also highly variable including calcareous and crystalline rocks, schists, alluvium, moraines… (see Table 1 for details per plot). Topography is very variable, plot elevation range from 800 (lower limit of the montane belt) to 1942 m a.s.l (subalpine belt). Plot slope is derived from a 1/25000 DEM and ranges from 1.46 to 41.93°.

2. Experimental or sampling design:

Forest types in the network (Table. 2) mainly consist of pure or mixed stands dominated by European beech (Fagus sylvatica), Silver fir (Abies alba) and Norway spruce (Picea abies), in association with various broadleaved species at low elevation and with Arolla pine (Pinus cembra) at high elevation. The plot network includes 23 plots that have not been managed for at least 40 years and 41 managed plots where the dominant management system is uneven-aged management and consists in single-tree or small-group selection cutting (Table. 2). Harvesting operations are monitored by recording harvested trees. Plots were installed from 1994 to 2004 and measured 2 to 5 times during the 1994-2015 period. Plot sizes range from to 0.25 ha to 1.875 ha. At the establishment of the plots, plot densities ranges from 181 to 1328 stems.ha-1 and plot basal areas ranges from 13.63 to 81.29 m2.ha-1 (Table. 2).

3. Research methods:

Tree diameters were measured using the following rules:

  1. Tree diameters were measured at breast height (1.3 m), from the ground on the uphill side of the stem. Trees leaning more than 45° were noted (code_status = 8881) and measured 1.3 along the underside of the tree.

  2. Tree diameters were measured to the nearest millimeters with a diameter tape (code_diam = 1). In some plots, however, diameters were measured with a caliper to the 5 nearest millimeters (code_diam = 2).

  3. Trees that forked above 1.3 m were measured below the fork whereas trees that forked below 1.3 m were measured as separate trees.

  4. During the first census, in case of existing deformities precluding normal dbh measurement, tree diameters were measured above or below the deformity. In case of deformities occurring between two successive census, the code_status of the tree was modified (code_status = 8883) and the dbh was not measured.

  5. Height of diameter measurement were marked on the trees (painting mark). Trees were individually identified in the field with alphanumeric identifiers (tree_id).

  6. New trees were recruited at each census. When a tree died between two census, the code_status of the tree was modified (code_status = 9990) and the dbh was not measured. In the same way, when a tree was logged between two census, the code_status of the tree was modified (code_status = 9991) and the dbh was not measured. Howewer, in 38 plots, the dbh of the dead standing trees (code_status = 9990) and the diameter of the stumps (code_status = 9991) were measured during the first census (Table. 3).

  7. When a tree was not found or when field workers forgot to measure a tree, the code_status of the tree was modified (code_status = 8880) and the dbh was not measured. In 41 plots, stem position was located with x, y coordinates (in the projected plan). In 23 plots only the stem position was located within subplots of 0.25 ha square called quadrats (Table. 3).

In 41 plots, stem position was located with x, y coordinates (in the projected plan). In 23 plots only the stem position was located within subplots of 0.25 ha square called quadrats (Table. 3). Stem height was measured in 58 plots on a subset of trees, mostly during the first census (Table. 3). It was defined as the length of the stem from ground to upmost growing tip either using the triangulation method (base distance and slope angle) with a clinometer and a measuring tape or using a Vertex IV ultrasonic hypsometer (Haglof).

Crown dimensions were measured in 0 plots on a subset of trees, during the first census (Table. 3). They were measured in four perpendicular directions (1 to 4) or two opposite directions (1 and 3). The first direction was on the uphill side of the stem, the third direction was opposite (downhill) and the second/fourth directions were respectively left/right of the first dimension. For each direction, crown height (height of the lowest branch) was measured either using triangulation method or Vertex IV. Crown radius (projected plan distance between the trunk and the outermost tip of the largest branch) was measured using a measuring tape.

Stem strata was eye-determined as follows: stand dominant height (H0) was divided in four intervals defining four strata, from the highest strata (strata 1: for tree with H ranging from 3/4 of H0 to H0) to the lowest strata (strata 4: for trees with H ranging from 0 to 1/2 of H0).

CLASS III. DATA SET STATUS AND ACCESSIBILITY

A. Status

Latest update: The dataset made available through this publication was processed on DATE TODO. R code use to check the data can be retrieved from the following website github.com/kunstler/AlpineForestData.

Metadata status: Metadata are complete to last update and are stored with data.

Data verification:

Stem dbh measurement were checked against previous values during the collection in the field to ensure consistency. After data entry, homogeneity in species code was checked, and xy coordinates were checked to conform to the plot dimension. We then identified outliers for growth and tree canopy allometry (stem height, crown radius and height) measurements and checked the corresponding data for field or entry errors. Outliers were identified as points classified as outlier by two methods. First, we fitted a quantile regression (package quantreg in R cran, see the R code at github.com/kunstler/AlpineForestData) at quantile 0.5% and 99.5% with a third degree smoothing function of the explicative variables (dbh for diameter annual growth, stem height and crown radius, and stem height for crown height) and identified outliers as the point outside this envelope. Secondly, we computed the Cook distance from a linear regression and identified outliers as points with a Cook distance above six times the mean Cook distance. The figures below present the points identified as outliers according each method that remains after data verification. We checked all points that were identified as outlier through both methods.

Figure 2 Diameter growth in function of initial dbh. and outliers identification (red point outlier identified with quantile regression; cross outlier identified based on the Cook distance).

Figure 3 Tree allometry (dbh – diameter at breast height in cm, h – tree height in m, crown radius in m, and crown depth in m) and outliers identification (red point outlier identified with quantile regression; cross outlier identified based on the Cook distance).

  • metadata_data_m.csv: Metatdata for tree measurements file
  • metadata_data_p.csv: Metatdata for plots description file
  • species_code.csv: Correspondence between species code and Latin name
  • status_code.csv: Definition of status code
